            p.
              Some have the opinion that #[code.sg-code em] and #[code.sg-code strong] are #[i semantic elements]
              while #[code.sg-code i] and #[code.sg-code b] are #[i formatting elements]
              (which should be #[b deprecated] in HTML5), however
              others might argue that
              given the flexibility of these, they can be used for other undefined phrasing content,
              such as scare quotes and mentions (for the former), and keywords
              and technical terms (for the latter).
              #[small However, #[s it&rsquo;s okay to use them interchangeably] one should remember not to use #[code.sg-code i] and #[code.sg-code b] for the meanings associated with #[code.sg-code em] and #[code.sg-code strong], respectively.]
            p.
              Use the #[code.sg-code sup] and #[code.sg-code sub] elements for when their presence
              is semantically required, not just when it looks good there.
              #[i(lang="la"): abbr(title="exampli gratia") E.g.], don&rsquo;t use superscripts
              for the abbreviation of ordinals. There are two reasons for this:
              1st,
              #[q superscripted ordinals are tiny and hard to read]
              #[cite (Matthew Butterick, #[time 2014])],
              but 2nd, and more importantly,
              the semantics would remain the same even if the superscript were removed.
              Use super/subscripts only when changing them to normal text would
              drastically affect their meaning. For example,
              in math: #[u f(x) = a#[sub 0]x#[sup 2] + a#[sub 1]x + a#[sub 2]],
              in chemical formulae: #[u dihydgogen oxide, or H#[sub 2]O, is commonly known as water], and
              in French abbreviations: #[u #[abbr(title="Mademoiselle") M#[sup lle]] Juliette].
